 issue) &#10;He has been in mainstream since he started school. He has just turned 7 and I found out today that we have a place for him in a special school. &#10;I refuse to keep him in MS any longer. It hasnt worked and I am not taking the risk that it might improve with a statement. &#10;He maybe able to re-enter MS at secondary if he gets the right help now.&#10;Until inclusion actually MEANS inclusion I would rather he was cared for and included in a specialist school. &#10;I am sure there are parents who have had great experiences of MS school but I have had enough. &#10;Its good you are starting to think about this now. I would call IPSEA for advice. They are very good. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="960" language="en" documentId="4946" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Becki J" date="30-03-10 23:25" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.netmums.com/coffeehouse/netmums-coffeehouse-archives-528/primary-school-admission-appeals-clinic-599/404307-special-educational-needs-re-mainstream-school-all.html" topic="mainstreaming" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="4946" notes="" title="Special Educational Needs re. Mainstream school"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="92"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="93" end="210"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="211" end="307"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="308" end="452"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="453" end="577"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="578" end="650"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="651" end="761"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="67" sofa="1" begin="762" end="857"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="71" sofa="1" begin="858" end="960"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63 67 71"/></xmi:XMI>